HEMORRHAGIC DISEASE, DOGS - USA (FLORIDA) (02)
***************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
<http://www.fas.org/promed/ahead>
See Also
Hemorrhagic disease, dogs - USA (Florida) 990112140110
[1
Date: Tue, 12 Jan 1999 12:16:10 -0500
From: Gary D Osweiler <osweiler@iastate.edu>

Just to rule out certain conditions, has there been any testing of
blood for vitamin K deficiency that might be induced by widespread
intoxication with an anticoagulant rodenticide? Is there a common
source of food or water? The clinical description appears very similar
to anticoagulant toxicosis in dogs, which often have marked pulmonary
hemorrhage and edema as well. However, lesions of viral pneumonia would
tend to lessen the anticoagulant possibility. This comment is offered
without knowledge of the epizootiology or other clinical, pathological
and chronological details.
--
Gary Osweiler, DVM
<osweiler@iastate.edu>
***
[2
Date: Tue, 12 Jan 1999 12:16:10 -0500
From: "Robert A. LaBudde" <ral@lcfltd.com>

Another possibility is Warfarin poisoning. Perhaps someone fed D-Con
rodent bait to the dogs.
--
Robert A. LaBudde
<ral@lcfltd.com>
